column25: The annual report  is prepared in accordance with the Danish Financial Statements Act.
column26: In our opinion, the consolidated financial statements and parent company financial statements give a true and fair view of the group's and the company's  financial position at 31 December 2015 and of the results of its operations and consolidated cash flows for the financial year 1 January - 31 December 2015.
column29: Amortisation, depreciation and impairment losses relating to intangible assets and property, plant and equipment comprise amortisation, depreciation and impairment losses for the financial year, calculated on the basis of the residual values and useful lives of the individual assets and impairment testing as well as gains and losses from the sale of intangible assets as well as property, plant and equipment.
column30: Cash comprises cash in hand and bank deposits.
column31: Prepayments comprise costs incurred concerning subsequent financial years. Prepayments are measured at cost.
column32: Staff costs comprise salaries and wages as well as social security contributions, pension contributions, etc. for entity staff.
column33: Other external expenses include expenses relating to the Entityâs ordinary activities, including expenses for premises, stationery and office supplies, marketing costs, etc. This item also includes write-downs of receivables recognised in current assets.
column34: Financial income and expenses include interest expenses on payables to group enterprises, payables and transactions in foreign currencies as well as tax surcharge under the Danish Tax Prepayment Scheme, etc.
column35: Other financial liabilities are measured at amortised cost, which usually corresponds to nominal value.
column36: Receivables are measured at amortised cost, usually equalling nominal value less write-downs for bad and doubtful debts.
column37: Revenue from the sale of manufactured goods and goods for resale is recognised in the income statement when delivery is made and risk has passed to the buyer. Revenue from the sale of services is recognised in the income statement when delivery is made to the buyer. Revenue is recognised net of VAT, duties and sales discounts and is measured at fair value of the consideration fixed.
